Time Series model fitting of Boston Weather Data

Vivek Vikram Magadi

April 13, 2018

R Markdown

Reading Data

The dataset that we have considered to work on is the Boston Weather dataset from July 2012 - August 2015. The dataset contains 5 different variables: 1. Temperature 2. Dewpoint 3. Humidity 4. Wind 5. Precipitation

As we shall see in the later part of the project, the precipitation variable shall not be considered as it is white noise.

Our data contains 1157 observations and 5 variables. Each observation is recorded on a daily basis.

Hypothesis : Our hypothesis is to forecast values of each variable. We have built two sets of models for comparison purposes. In the first set of models we model each variable as a univariate time series using ARIMA/SARIMA. In the second set of models we model a Vector Auto-Regressive model on all 4 variables. Then we compare to see if the Vector Auto-Regressive model gave us a better fit or did the Arima/Sarima models give us a better fit.

The timestamp was split into day, month and year variables starting from August 2015 to July 2012. we shall club them into a single variable and then reverse the order of the observations.

Mean Difference

First we subtract the mean from all the variables to center them on the X axis.

Plotting all the time series

From the above Time Series plots we can see that precipitation almost looks like white noise; Temperature and Dewpoint have seasonal patterns ( looks like a yearly pattern).

Decomposing Time Series plots

The above plots show a decomposed version of each time series by using loess. Temperature and Dewpoint are considered on a yearly basis whereas humidity, wind and precipitation are considered on a monthly basis.

Interpretting ACF and PACF

Humidity

We can see that the lags in AutoCorrelation and Partial Autocorrelation plots die off after a certain number of significant lags so we can assume stationarity. To quantify stationarity we shall conduct the dickey-fuller test.

By looking at the significant lags of the ACF we determine the MA lag term and that of the PACF determines the ACf term. ACF : 3 significant lags. Also there looks like there exists a seasonal pattern in the data as denoted by lag 12 and it’s surroundings. PACF : 2 significant lags. The seasonal lags persist in the PACF plot as well.

Dewpoint

The PACF plot indicates that a significant correlation occurs at lag 2. The ACF plot indicates that an auto-regressive model might be a right fit to the model as indicated by the slow decay in the correlations.

Precipitation

The ACF plot does not present any significant lags. But it is noticed that lags of same correlation occur at regular intervals of 4. The PACF plot shows that the significant correlations occur only at lags 3 and 22. This series mainly indicates white noise and shall not be considered for our analysis.

Wind

The ACf tells us that there is a significant correlation at lag 1. Also a seasonal lag of 5 might be present. The PACF does not present us with much information apart from the fact that some seasonal lag might exist.

Temperature

The ACF plot shows slow decay indicating an auto-regressive model might be appropriate over here. Looking at the PACF we can see that a significant correlation occurs at lag 2 followed by some seasonal variation.

Spectral Analysis

Except wind all the other variables have the trend that as the frequency gets higher, the amplitude gets smaller. Humidity shows that it the frequency with the highest amplitude indicates that it changes every ~90 days(1 season). Wind also looks like the frequency with the highest amplitude occurs at a cycle of about 80 - 90 days. Temperature and Dewpoint spectral plots are similar with dewpoint having a higher amplitude at corresponding frequencies.

Fitting Data

We noticed that there was seasonality in temperature and dewpoint We shall get rid of them by harmonic regression. A frequency of 3/N was taken. Temperature.

Dewpoint

We shall work on the residuals of harmonic regression applied on temperature and dewpoint variables.

Checking stationarity via Dickey - Fuller Test

Dickey- fuller test checks the null hypothesis whether unit roots of the characteristic equation is present. If the p-value of the test is below 0.05 we reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative saying that all the roots of the charactersitic equation are greater than 1 ie the roots lie outside the unit circle.

Cross Correlation Plots

Humidity lags temperature. Thus humidity can be used as a predictor for temperature.

Humidity slightly leads dewpoint. Dewpoint might be a useful predictor for Humidity.

Humidity slightly leads wind. Wind might be a useful predictor for humidity.

There is no strict lag/lead relationship that we can infer from this plot. We can just say that both the variables cause each other just like a cycle.

Dewpoint lags wind at lag 1,2 and 3. Dewpoint might be a useful predictor for wind.

Wind leads Temperature at lags 2,3 and 4. Temperature might be a useful predictor for wind.

Now all the time series are stationary
